1. Acknowledgement: EMerge
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Copyright (C) Robert Fennis and EMerge contributors.
Upstream: https://github.com/FennisRobert/EMerge

Early development of rapidfem's frequency-domain backend used EMerge
(GPL-2.0-or-later) as a reference implementation. Those files have since
been rewritten so that no EMerge source remains:

  * The core finite-element kernels — the canonical Nédélec first-kind
    order-2 element (`tet_assembly_r2.rs`), the barycentric integration
    coefficients (`coefficients.rs`), the surface Robin/port assembly
    (`tri_assembly_r2.rs`) and the field reconstruction (`interp.rs`) —
    were re-derived from primary mathematics with an independent symbolic
    derivation harness (see `derivations/`) and are validated entrywise
    against it. The former `tet_assembly.rs` / `tri_assembly.rs` ports were
    removed.

  * The remaining modules (`assembly.rs`, `sparam.rs`, `waveguide.rs`,
    `materials.rs`, `quadrature.rs`, `mesh.rs`, `basis.rs`, `constants.rs`,
    `touchstone.rs`) implement standard, non-copyrightable content —
    textbook electromagnetic formulas (Pozar, Jackson, Collin), published
    numerical tables (Dunavant; Eisenberg & Malvern), the public Touchstone
    file format, and generic FEM data structures / assembly orchestration —
    re-expressed with primary-source citations.

rapidfem remains under GPL-3.0-or-later with the Gmsh additional permission.
EMerge is acknowledged here in good faith as the original architectural
reference.

